File system hierarchy standard
The root directory (/) is the starting point for all files. 
* /bin & /sbin: Essential executable programs (binaries). /bin contains command for all 
users (like ls or cp), while /sbin is for system administration (like reboot).
* /etc: The "nerve center" containing all system-wide configuration files.
* /home: Personal space for regular users (e.g., /home/username).
* /root: The separate home directory for the system administrator (root user).
* /var: Stores "variable" data like system logs (/var/log) and databases.
* /tmp: Temporary files created by apps; usually wiped on reboot.
* /usr: Contains user-related programs and libraries. Modern distros often link /bin to /usr/
bin.
* /boot: Vital files for starting the system, including the Linux kernel.
* /dev: Location of all hardware device files.
